Executive function is one of the few cognitive domains where targeted practice often produces noticeable improvements because it relies on habits, environments, and strategies as much as raw ability.

Executive function isn’t one thing—it’s a collection of control systems that help you turn intentions into actions. A useful way to think about it is as the “CEO” of your mind.

Here’s a breakdown:

Executive Function	What it does	Example
Working memory	Hold and manipulate information	Keeping three tasks in mind while planning your day
Inhibition	Resist impulses	Not checking your phone while working
Cognitive flexibility	Switch strategies	Adapting when Plan A fails
Planning	Build sequences toward goals	Breaking a project into milestones
Prioritization	Decide what matters now	Doing the important task before the urgent one
Task initiation	Starting without procrastination	Beginning the first paragraph
Sustained attention	Stay engaged	Reading for an hour
Monitoring	Notice mistakes	Catching yourself drifting
Emotional regulation	Prevent emotions from hijacking decisions	Responding instead of reacting

